Summary__c: Since 2004, the American Red Cross has been working with the Tanzania Red Cross to help prevent HIV among vulnerable populations in Tanzania.  Beginning in 2009, we expanded our activities to include care and support services for people living with HIV.  Currently, we are working in the Shinyanga region, western Tanzania, to decrease the number of people contracting HIV, reduce AIDS-related deaths and improve the quality of life for the chronically ill, including people living with HIV and orphans and vulnerable children.  Additionally, we are working to improve knowledge about HIV at the community level and to strengthen the capacity of the Tanzania Red Cross in HIV programming.  In total, we aim to provide services directly to approximately 2,700 people, while an additional 35,000 people will be reached through community-based educational activities that focus on preventing HIV and reducing the stigma and discrimination associated with this disease.
Name: Tanzania Integrated HIV/AIDS

Summary__c: In an effort to adapt current programming to better fit the needs of local communities, the American Red Cross has developed an assessment model to be piloted in ten countries in the Latin America and Caribbean Region that is designed to be a holistic, multi-sector analysis of community risks. The assessment process is led by communities themselves and allows them to identify their key needs and vulnerabilities, as well as the capacities and resources they have to enhance resilience. Through this pilot, the American Red Cross and local partners will develop tools, training manuals, a compilation of lessons learned, and a roll-out strategy that can potentially be replicated in other parts of the world. The American Red Cross will work with local Red Cross partners to pilot this assessment model with 126 communities in the Bahamas, Belize, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, El Salvador, Guyana, Nicaragua, Panama and Peru. As a pilot, this assessment will directly benefit almost 3,500 people across all ten countries.
Name: RITA - Belize

Summary__c: Africa is experiencing the most rapid urbanizing population in the world with a current urban annual growth rate of 3.3 percent. The municipalities of Gulu and Lira in northern Uganda and have experienced rapid population growth over the past 20 years, leading to extremely congested neighborhoods, especially within low-income areas. Residents face three major hazards: fires, floods and traffic accidents. This project will strengthen the resilience of 10 vulnerable communities in Gulu and Lira to reduce the risks associated with floods, fires and inadequate emergency response systems. The project will work with the Uganda Red Cross to form Community Fire Response teams, engage local Red Cross youth in community clean-up days, and train motorcycle taxis as first responders when accidents occur, benefiting an estimated 85,000 people.
Sub_Sector__c: Community-Based Disaster Preparedness;Urban Disaster Preparedness;First Responder Training;Capacity Building;Project Management
Name: Prepare Uganda: Reducing Risks in Urban Communities - Full

Summary__c: Vulnerable communities throughout the Caribbean are frequently exposed to natural disasters, particularly severe weather. The American Red Cross is helping community members and Red Cross partners in the Bahamas, Belize and St Lucia prepare for future disasters. Beginning in 2011, through the support of the American Red Cross, Red Cross partners in the Bahamas, Belize and St Lucia have been training local staff and volunteers on disaster preparedness best practices such as conducting detailed assessments and supporting the development of disaster preparedness plans to address risks and vulnerabilities identified in disaster prone communities. The American Red Cross is also helping Red Cross partners in these countries train staff, volunteers and community members in first aid, basic search and rescue, psychological first aid, response coordination and shelter management, and is undertaking disaster mitigation projects such as digging drainage ditches or installing straps that help secure roofs from the high winds of hurricanes. This initiative is a partnership of the American Red Cross, the U.S. Agency for International Development’s Office of U.S. Foreign Disaster Assistance, and Red Cross partners in the Bahamas, Belize and St Lucia. It is expected to benefit a total of 75,000 people across the region, including 8,500 in the Bahamas, 55,200 in Belize and more than 11,500 in St Lucia.
Name: Saving Lives in the Caribbean Through Preparedness - Belize

Summary__c: The purpose of this grant is to allow the Global Disaster Preparedness Center (GDPC) to build upon the foundation set during FY13 by: (1) extending the investment in effective knowledge management practices; (2) validating and expanding learning through research and outreach; and (3) cultivating a greater sense of ownership of the GDPC amongst national societies while simultaneously forging stronger ties with the wider humanitarian community. The strategy behind the GDPC’s proposed activities for FY14 is to provide services that bolster the disaster preparedness work of Red Cross partners around the world and to offer services that are driven by the interests of national societies and other partners in the global Red Cross and Red Crescent network.
Name: GDPC FY14 ARCT
